// @skip-os: linux
// struct timeval's tv_usec is suseconds_t, which is i32 on macOS but i64 on
// 64-bit Linux. This fixture declares tv_usec: i32 (+ i32 opaque padding),
// which is the macOS layout; on Linux @cLayout correctly rejects it as not
// matching the header. The @cOpaque feature under test is platform-independent
// — only this particular struct's layout is macOS-specific — so the test runs
// on macOS and is skipped on Linux rather than asserting a wrong layout there.
//
// @cOpaque marks a field as filler with no C counterpart, so @cLayout skips it.
//
// Needed for structs padded out to a size C dictates: node-milo's `Rusage` names only
// ru_utime/ru_stime but must be 144 bytes because that is what getrusage() writes, so it
// pads with _p0.._pD. Those fields do not exist in `struct rusage`, so @cLayout emitted
// `offsetof(struct rusage, _p0)` — ill-formed C — and the struct could not be verified
// at all. The prefix rule covers an omitted *tail*, not opaque padding in the middle.
//
// The real fields must still be checked; `struct timeval` is the same shape as Rusage's
// leading members, so this pins both halves: named fields verified, filler ignored, and
// the size assert still counts the filler (that is the point of declaring it).
@cLayout("struct timeval", "sys/time.h")
extern struct Timeval {
    tv_sec: i64,
    // Real: suseconds_t (i32) + 4 bytes of tail padding. Declaring the padding keeps
    // sizeOf<Timeval>() honest at 16 without claiming C has a field named `_pad`.
    tv_usec: i32,
    @cOpaque _pad: i32,
}

fn main() {
    // @expect: true
    print(sizeOf<Timeval>() == 16)
    // @expect: true
    print(offsetOf<Timeval>("tv_sec") == 0)
    // @expect: true
    print(offsetOf<Timeval>("tv_usec") == 8)
}
